You rubbed your temple, trying to find some sort of moment for relaxation. The moments of triumph from four years ago seemed distant now. The young, energetic candidate who had promised to build a bridge to the 21st century was now a man weighed down by defeats and mistakes, real and perceived. You were confident, maybe too confident. You’d told yourself that the debates had gone well, that the voters cared more about jobs and health care than your personal life. But in the end, you weren’t been able to overcome the relentless drumbeat of Republican attacks or the weariness of an electorate ready for change.

As you walked to the stage, you could feel the weight of the moment pressing down on you. You made a simple speech about accepting the results of the election, and continuing the fight, even outside of the Oval Office. Although the crowd cheered, you felt as if it was almost out of pity. The screen flickered with images of cheering crowds in Kansas, in Indiana, in Ohio, states that had been expected to lean Republican but had turned out in force for the GOP. The electoral map was painted a harsh red across the Midwest and much of the South, with only a few splashes of blue along the coasts and in Illinois. It didn’t matter how much he won by, it was still decisive enough to leave no doubt, at least in your own mind, that you were a failure. States that you won easily in ’92, flipped. The ''Third Way Democrat'' movement that you spearheaded seems to be permanently dead.

You rubbed your temple, trying to find some sort of moment for relaxation. The moments of triumph from four years ago seemed distant now. The young, energetic candidate who had promised to build a bridge to the 21st century was now a man weighed down by defeats and mistakes, real and perceived. You were confident, maybe too confident. You’d told yourself that the debates had gone well, that the voters cared more about jobs and health care than your personal life. But in the end, you weren’t been able to overcome the relentless drumbeat of Republican attacks or the weariness of an electorate ready for change.

Hillary sat beside you, her hand resting on your knee. She was quiet, but her presence steadied you, as it always has. You glanced at her, seeing in her eyes a mixture of sorrow and determination. ''She’s gonna keep fightin’, that’s my girl.'', you said in your head. She always did.

You took a deep breath and stood, smoothing your tie. You knew what you had to do. It wasn’t the first time you faced defeat, but it was the hardest. As you walked to the stage, you could feel the weight of the moment pressing down on you. You made a simple speech about accepting the results of the election, and continuing the fight, even outside of the Oval Office. Although the crowd cheered, you felt as if it was almost out of pity. You still felt like there was work to do, and that the American people cut you short. As you left the stage, the applause fading behind you, you couldn’t shake the feeling that your time in the spotlight had come to an end.
